description:
## Goal

Define the structured `Diagnostic` type that every error and warning in the system will produce. Replaces:

- The stage-tagged `String`s plumbed through `Result<_, String>` everywhere.
- The existing `ir_typer::Diagnostic { fn_name, kind, message }` (`src/ir_typer.rs:546-556`), which gets folded into the new type.

## Dependencies

- Requires .20.1 (Span).
- Independent of .20.2 / .20.3 / .20.4 — this ticket defines the *type*; wiring is .20.7.

## Module layout

`src/diag/diagnostic.rs` (new module, sibling of .20.1's `span.rs` and `source_map.rs`).

## Design

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum Severity { Error, Warning, Note, Help }

/// Stable string code identifying the diagnostic class. Used for:
/// - documentation cross-reference ("see fz docs for type/unreachable-arm")
/// - --deny / --allow filtering in the future
/// - JSON machine output
///
/// Format: `<stage>/<kind>`. Examples:
///   "lex/unterminated-string"
///   "parse/expected-token"
///   "resolve/unknown-module"
///   "macro/expansion-loop"
///   "lower/unbound"
///   "type/unreachable-arm"
///   "type/empty-narrowing"
///   "codegen/schema-missing"
///   "runtime/assertion-failed"
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Hash)]
pub struct DiagCode(pub &'static str);

/// A span with an optional short label rendered under the caret.
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct SpanLabel {
    pub span: Span,
    /// Short text drawn under the underline. Keep it ≤ ~40 chars; long
    /// explanations belong in `notes`. May be empty.
    pub label: String,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct Diagnostic {
    pub severity: Severity,
    pub code: DiagCode,
    /// Headline. One short sentence. Renders on the first line:
    ///   error[lower/unbound]: unbound name `foo`
    pub message: String,
    /// Primary span: the *one* location the diagnostic is "about". Drawn
    /// with `^^^^` underline; gets the bold/red color (when colors on).
    pub primary: SpanLabel,
    /// Secondary spans: "this is where it was defined", "the call site".
    /// Drawn with `----` underline; less prominent color. Order matters
    /// for rendering: top-down in the source.
    pub secondaries: Vec<SpanLabel>,
    /// Long-form explanation lines. Each renders as `= note: <line>`.
    pub notes: Vec<String>,
    /// Suggested fixes. Each renders as `= help: <line>`. Text only in v1;
    /// structured fixits are future work.
    pub helps: Vec<String>,
    /// Macro-expansion lineage. When the primary span has
    /// `SpanOrigin::Expanded { macro_call, definition }`, the renderer
    /// emits an "expanded from `<macro>` at <macro_call>" trailer. This
    /// field is the explicit form for diagnostics that synthesize their
    /// own lineage (e.g. errors inside a quote'd body).
    pub expanded_from: Vec<Span>,
}

impl Diagnostic {
    pub fn error(code: DiagCode, message: impl Into<String>, primary: Span) -> Self;
    pub fn warning(code: DiagCode, message: impl Into<String>, primary: Span) -> Self;
    pub fn with_label(self, label: impl Into<String>) -> Self;
    pub fn with_secondary(self, span: Span, label: impl Into<String>) -> Self;
    pub fn with_note(self, note: impl Into<String>) -> Self;
    pub fn with_help(self, help: impl Into<String>) -> Self;
}
```

### Why `&'static str` for DiagCode

The set of codes is closed and small (< 100). Using `&'static str` makes them grep-able, link-able from docs, and zero-cost to compare. A future enum is an option but loses the documentation-as-grep-target affordance. Each module owns its code constants:

```rust
// in src/ir_typer.rs
pub const TYPE_UNREACHABLE_ARM: DiagCode = DiagCode("type/unreachable-arm");
```

A consolidated `src/diag/codes.rs` listing every code with a one-line description is part of this ticket's deliverable — it's the single source of truth for the documentation index.

### Severity model

`Note` and `Help` are *attached to* other diagnostics, not freestanding. Top-level diagnostics are `Error` or `Warning`. The renderer (.20.6) draws notes/helps as the `= note:` / `= help:` lines under the primary block. This mirrors rustc's structure and is what produces readable output.

A `Diagnostic` doesn't carry sub-diagnostics — they're folded into the `notes`/`helps` lists. If a future need arises for "nested diagnostic" (e.g. "this error was caused by the following sub-error"), introduce a `causes: Vec<Diagnostic>` field then; don't pre-design it.

## Accumulator

```rust
pub struct Diagnostics {
    diags: Vec<Diagnostic>,
}

impl Diagnostics {
    pub fn new() -> Self;
    pub fn push(&mut self, d: Diagnostic);
    pub fn extend(&mut self, other: Diagnostics);
    pub fn has_errors(&self) -> bool;
    pub fn iter(&self) -> impl Iterator<Item = &Diagnostic>;
    pub fn into_vec(self) -> Vec<Diagnostic>;
}
```

Stages return `Result<T, Diagnostics>` where the error case carries *all* collected diagnostics. v1 stages may bail on the first error (Diagnostics with len 1), but the wire type already supports multi-error so future tickets can flip without breaking callers.

For warnings during a successful stage (e.g. ir_typer's unreachable-arm), the stage returns `Ok((value, Diagnostics))` where the warnings ride along. The driver (.20.7) renders them after the stage completes.

## DiagCode taxonomy seed

The initial code set, populated as part of this ticket in `src/diag/codes.rs`. Each is `pub const NAME: DiagCode = DiagCode("…")` plus a doc comment that becomes the documentation entry. Errors expected on day one (drawn from the eprintln! survey in the .20 epic):

- `lex/unterminated-string`, `lex/invalid-char`, `lex/invalid-number`
- `parse/expected-token`, `parse/unexpected-token`, `parse/duplicate-moduledoc`, `parse/duplicate-doc`, `parse/unknown-attribute`, `parse/dangling-doc`, `parse/macro-call-shape`
- `resolve/alias-outside-module`, `resolve/import-outside-module`, `resolve/unknown-module`, `resolve/ambiguous-name`
- `macro/not-a-defmacro`, `macro/expansion-loop`, `macro/arg-reification-failed`, `macro/body-failed`, `macro/return-decode-failed`, `macro/bad-item-shape`, `macro/leftover-unquote`, `macro/post-resolution-leftover`
- `lower/unsupported`, `lower/unbound`, `lower/arity-mismatch`, `lower/post-expansion-leftover`
- `type/unreachable-arm`, `type/empty-narrowing` (.24.6 already produces these — rename/refile from the current `DiagKind` enum)
- `codegen/schema-missing`, `codegen/trampoline-overflow` (these are panics today; .20.7 decides which become diagnostics)
- `runtime/assertion-failed`, `runtime/division-by-zero`, `runtime/index-out-of-bounds`, `runtime/no-matching-clause`, `runtime/builtin-error`

This list is the punch-list for the wiring ticket (.20.7) — every code corresponds to at least one existing error site.

## ir_typer::Diagnostic transition

`src/ir_typer.rs::DiagKind` / `Diagnostic` are subsumed by the new type. ir_typer keeps producing diagnostics; it now constructs `diag::Diagnostic` directly. The `ir_typer::collect_diagnostics` return type changes from `Vec<ir_typer::Diagnostic>` to `Diagnostics`. The `ir_codegen::CompiledModule.diagnostics` field switches type accordingly.

The current `fn_name` field becomes a `secondary` span pointing at the fn definition (after .20.4 lands), or drops out if redundant with the primary span.

## Deliverables

- `src/diag/` module with `span.rs` (from .20.1), `source_map.rs` (from .20.1), `diagnostic.rs`, `codes.rs`.
- New `Diagnostic` / `Diagnostics` / `SpanLabel` / `DiagCode` / `Severity` types.
- `DiagCode` constants covering every stage (the seed list above).
- `ir_typer::Diagnostic` removed; ir_typer constructs `diag::Diagnostic` directly.
- `CompiledModule.diagnostics: Diagnostics` (replacing `Vec<ir_typer::Diagnostic>`).
- Tests:
  - Build a `Diagnostic` with builder methods; verify shape.
  - Round-trip a `Diagnostics { Vec<Diagnostic> }` through extend/iter.
  - Verify ir_typer's `.24.6` UnreachableArm path still produces a (now-richer) diagnostic.

## Non-goals

- Rendering (.20.6).
- Wiring the rest of the pipeline (.20.7).
- JSON output (v2).
- Fixit-style structured suggestions (`helps` is text-only).
